threats.description:
The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary injecting malicious code into the compromised information system or IoT device, which can subsequently be launched "manually" by users, automatically when a certain condition is met (a certain date occurs, user logs into the system, etc.), or using default authentication data, as well as the possibility of unauthorized injection of the adversary's own data for processing in the compromised information system, effectively accomplishing illegal use of others' computing resources, and blocking device operation when executing certain commands.
This threat is caused by:
the presence of software vulnerabilities;
weaknesses in antivirus protection and access control measures;
the presence of an open Telnet port on the IoT device (for IoT devices only).
Realization of this threat is possible:
if the compromised user works with files from untrusted sources;
if they have software installation privileges;
if the IoT device owner has not changed the device's credentials (factory password and login)

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary escalating their privileges in a compromised system (obtaining the privileges of compromised programs) by exploiting program errors and executing arbitrary code with their privileges.
This threat is caused by weaknesses in input data and command validation mechanisms, as well as access control measures.
Realization of this threat is possible under the following conditions:
the compromised program has elevated privileges in the system;
the compromised program accepts input data from other programs or from the user;
the adversary has the ability to transmit data to the compromised program

The threat consists of the possibility of forcing a transition to using BIOS/UEFI containing vulnerabilities.
This threat is caused by weaknesses in BIOS/UEFI software update control technologies.
When using BIOS/UEFI update technology, the following situation may arise (conditions characterizing the situation are listed in chronological order):
a computer has a certain version of BIOS/UEFI for which no vulnerabilities are known at the time of its operation;
due to certain circumstances, BIOS/UEFI undergoes an update procedure, while saving the previous version of BIOS/UEFI in case of system rollback;
data about the existence of vulnerabilities in the previous version of BIOS/UEFI is published;
a system failure occurs, as a result of which the current (new) version of BIOS/UEFI becomes inoperable (for example, its integrity is violated);
the user performs a standard system recovery procedure - rolls back the system to the previous working state

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary gaining access to hidden/protected directories or files through various actions on the file system (adding additional characters to the file path; accessing files that are not explicitly specified in the application window).
This threat is caused by weaknesses in the access control mechanism for file system objects.
Realization of this threat is possible under the following conditions:
the adversary has access rights to some file system objects;
lack of validation of user-entered data;
the compromised program has excessively high file access privileges that are not intended for processing by it

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary changing computer hardware operating modes through unauthorized BIOS/UEFI reconfiguration, which allows:
affecting overall computer performance or causing malfunctions by changing system bus frequency, data transmission mode over communication channels, etc.;
temporarily ensuring computer inoperability by reducing input voltage, disabling cooling systems;
causing physical failure of individual computer hardware elements by setting unacceptable device operating parameters (threshold value for device shutdown during overheating, input voltage, etc.).
This threat is caused by weaknesses in BIOS/UEFI management access control technologies.
Realization of this threat is possible if the adversary has privileges to modify the corresponding BIOS/UEFI configuration parameters

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary performing unauthorized access to protected information bypassing standard mechanisms using non-standard interfaces (including command-line access bypassing graphical interface).
This threat is caused by weaknesses in protected information access control measures and input data filtering weaknesses.
Realization of this threat is possible if the adversary has:
the ability to enter arbitrary data in the address bar;
information about the path to the protected resource;
the ability to change the input data entry interface

The threat consists of the possibility of performing destructive software impact on the compromised system or indirect destructive software impact through it on other systems by gaining unauthorized access to virtual machine images.
This threat is caused by weaknesses in access control measures for virtual machine images implemented in virtualization software.
Realization of this threat can lead to:
confidentiality violation of protected information processed using virtual machines created based on unauthorized modified images;
integrity violation of programs installed on virtual machines;
availability violation of virtual machine resources;
botnet creation by injecting malicious software into virtual machine images used as templates (reference images)

The threat consists of the possibility of direct access (access from architecture levels lower than the operating system level) to data stored on machine storage media, or recovery of data from residual information read from machine storage media.
This threat is caused by weaknesses in the mechanism for deleting information from machine storage media - information deleted from machine storage media can in most cases be recovered.
Realization of this threat is possible under the following conditions:
information deletion from machine storage media occurred without using methods (techniques, algorithms) of guaranteed data erasure (for example, physical destruction of machine storage media);
technological features of machine storage media do not lead to guaranteed information destruction upon receiving a data erasure command;
information was not stored in cryptographically transformed form

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary changing the sequence of actions performed by compromised applications using in their work technologies for process management based on current time and information system state (for example, current values of global variables, presence of running processes, etc.), or the possibility of modifying settings and changing operating modes of industrial robots leading to interference in the production process and theft of information stored in robot memory (source code, product parameters, etc.).
This threat is based on weaknesses in the synchronization and state management mechanism allowing the adversary to make changes to its operation at certain time intervals, or the absence of authentication and authorization mechanisms.
Realization of this threat is possible if the adversary has the ability to:
control the state of the compromised application (algorithm execution stages) or industrial robots;
track time moments when the compromised application temporarily interrupts its work with global data;
perform destructive actions at certain time moments (for example, make changes to a data file or change the contents of a memory cell)

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary discrediting protective mechanisms functioning on the hypervisor basis that prevent unauthorized access to virtual machine images due to hypervisor update errors.
This threat is caused by the dependence of each virtual device and each virtualized access subject functioning, as well as the entire virtual infrastructure (or its part if more than one hypervisor is used) on hypervisor operability.
Realization of this threat is possible if errors occur during the hypervisor update process:
failures during its update;
updates during which new errors are introduced into the hypervisor code;
updates during which program code is introduced into the hypervisor causing hypervisor incompatibility with its functioning environment;
other information security incidents

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary unlawfully exfiltrating protected information from the system, as well as transmitting control commands by non-standard (inconspicuous, hidden) placement in data legitimately transmitted over the network (or saved to alienable media) open data by masking it as service protocols, hiding it in the flow of other data (steganography), using hidden pixels ("tracking pixels"), etc.
This threat is caused by insufficiency of information protection measures against leakage, as well as data flow control.
Realization of this threat is possible with:
the adversary having rights in the compromised system to install specialized software implementing functions for embedding their own information into data packets formed for transmission in the system;
access to data transmission channels;
user visits to websites on the Internet and opening emails containing hidden pixels

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary conducting indirect destructive software impact on the compromised system with a large volume of network traffic generated by third-party servers in response to network requests formed by the adversary on behalf of the compromised system. Network traffic generated by third-party servers significantly exceeds the volume of network requests formed by the adversary.
This threat is caused by weaknesses in compromised information system firewall measures, measures to control authenticity of network requests on third-party servers, as well as weaknesses in the open systems interaction model.
Realization of this threat is possible if the adversary possesses:
information about third-party servers with insufficient network request authenticity control measures;
information about the compromised system's network address;
special software implementing network packet generation functions

The threat consists of the possibility of denying a legitimate user resource allocation for processing their requests due to an adversary exhausting free resources in the system by their unauthorized exclusion from the general resource pool based on "resource leak" or "resource allocation" techniques.
This threat is caused by weaknesses in the computing resource distribution control mechanism between users, as well as compromised information system firewall measures and network request authenticity control on third-party servers.
Realization of this threat is possible if the adversary possesses:
information about the format and parameters of destructive impacts on the system leading to exclusion ("leak" or "allocation") of free resources from the general resource pool of the compromised system;
privileges sufficient to conduct destructive impacts ("leak" or "allocation") in the compromised system;
administrators' lack of ability: for "resource leak" technique – to reboot the system while the adversary is sending a large number of resource allocation requests, and for "resource allocation" technique – forced release of resources allocated by malicious process requests

The threat consists of the possibility of losing information stored on a formatted medium, often without the possibility of its recovery, due to intentional or accidental execution of the storage medium formatting procedure.
This threat is caused by weakness in measures restricting access to the system function of storage medium formatting.
Factors affecting realization of this threat include:
time elapsed since formatting;
type of storage medium;
type of medium file system;
intensity of medium interaction after formatting, etc.

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary escalating privileges in systems using code digital signature as binding information between a program and its privileges by compromising the code signing mechanism.
This threat is caused by weaknesses in the code signing mechanism.
Realization of this threat is possible under the following conditions:
the compromised code is written using a framework supporting code signing;
the compromised code is signed by the vendor (software provider);
the adversary has the ability to inject code into the compromised computer

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary obtaining access rights to protected information by intercepting exceptions/signals generated by a code section executed with elevated privileges (privileged function block) and containing commands for protected information management.
This threat is caused by the fact that calling program functions in privileged mode implies disabling access control mechanisms for them.
Realization of this threat is possible under the following conditions:
the compromised program is written in a programming language supporting the privileged block mechanism (for example, Java);
in the compromised program, privileged block calls are made in an unsafe manner (public declaration of internal functions used, exception generation from privileged block used);
the adversary possesses rights sufficient to intercept program exceptions in the system

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary gaining unauthorized access to information infrastructure by obtaining the right to control the industrial control system included in it through exploitation of its software vulnerabilities or technological data transmission protocol weaknesses.
This threat is caused by the presence in the industrial control system of program network interaction interfaces and, as a consequence, the possibility of unauthorized access to this system, as well as insufficient network traffic filtering measures and antivirus protection.
Realization of this threat is possible if the adversary has rights to interact with the industrial control system. Realization of this threat may lead to:
blocking or distortion (incorrect execution) of technological process control task execution algorithms, direct enterprise equipment control;
disruption of normal technological process flow;
partial or complete stoppage of technological processes without (or with) equipment failure;
emergency situation in critical information infrastructure system

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary collecting and analyzing information processed using a mobile device through use of special software embedded by the user in the mobile device system software, as well as embedded in mobile programs disguised as a software platform for their development by other companies.
This threat is caused by the presence of multiple data transmission channels in the mobile device, as well as difficulty in controlling information flows in such a device.
Realization of this threat is possible if mobile devices are used by users. Collected information may include:
user and contacting persons' personal data (gender, age, religious and political views, etc.);
restricted access information (browser history, user contact list, call history, etc.);
environmental data (current mobile device location, movement routes, presence of wireless networks within access radius);
video data captured by mobile device video cameras;
audio data captured by device microphone

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary injecting malicious code into a user's computer when visiting infected sites. The adversary identifies the most visited sites by the user, then compromises them and injects malicious code into them. This threat is caused by weaknesses in antivirus protection measures, as well as absence of firewall rules. Realization of this threat is possible with:
unrestricted user access to the Internet;
the adversary possessing information about sites visited by the user

The threat consists of the possibility of remote malicious code execution through creation of applications using bypass of protection mechanisms built into the operating system.
This threat is caused by processor errors (for example, errors in Intel Haswell generation processors) allowing bypass of protection mechanisms built into the operating system (for example, ASLR mechanism) through creation of special applications.
Realization of this threat is possible with: collision initiation in target buffer table - with its help, memory areas where specific code fragments are located can be discovered;
application creation using these code fragments to bypass the protection mechanism;
launching this application in conjunction with an exploit of some operating system vulnerability to create the possibility of remote malicious code execution

The threat consists of the possibility of gaining access to protected memory from a program not possessing corresponding rights as a result of exploiting vulnerabilities allowing bypass of the access control mechanism implemented by the central processor.
Realization of this threat is caused by vulnerabilities related to memory access control errors based on speculative instruction execution by the processor. The access control error is caused by the following factors:
1) absence of process access rights verification for read areas during speculative operation execution, including when reading from RAM;
2) absence of cache clearing from erroneous speculative execution results;
3) storage of operating system kernel data in process address space.
Realization of this threat is possible due to processors having hardware vulnerabilities and absence of corresponding updates

The threat consists of the possibility of an adversary disrupting functionality ("bypassing") of tools implementing artificial intelligence technologies.
This threat is caused by the following reasons:
- absence of necessary data in the training sample;
- presence of machine learning model deficiencies;
